The paper deals with complexity theory and approximation algorithms for dense constraint satisfaction problems (CSPs), which are typically studied in computer science theory. The use of the term "birthday repetition" suggests a connection to probability theory, which is often used in complexity theory. The paper also cites previous work in computational complexity (Aaronson, Impagliazzo, and Moshkovitz), further supporting the likelihood of cs.CC as a relevant sub-category. The use of linear and semidefinite programming relaxations suggests a connection to optimization and information theory (cs.IT), while the study of approximation algorithms and integrality gaps suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses geometric embeddings and fine-grained complexity, which are relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG) and machine learning (cs.LG).
